{
  "Accuracy refers to how close a measurement is to the:": "",
  "True or accepted value": "",
  "Other repeated measurements": "",
  "Mean of the data set": "",
  "Median value": "",
  "Accuracy describes closeness to the true (accepted) value. Closeness to other measurements is precision, not accuracy.": "",
  "Precision refers to how close repeated measurements are to:": "",
  "Zero": "",
  "Each other": "",
  "The true value": "",
  "The expected theoretical value": "",
  "Precision measures reproducibility — how closely repeated measurements agree with one another, regardless of whether they are near the true value.": "",
  "The formula for percent error is:": "",
  "(experimental + accepted) / 2 × 100%": "",
  "experimental × accepted / 100%": "",
  "accepted / experimental × 100%": "",
  "|experimental − accepted| / accepted × 100%": "",
  "Percent error compares the experimental value to the accepted value using their absolute difference divided by the accepted value, then multiplied by 100%.": "",
  "A set of measurements is described as precise but not accurate. This means the values are:": "",
  "Neither close together nor close to the true value": "",
  "Close together but far from the true value": "",
  "Close to the true value but spread apart": "",
  "Both close together and close to the true value": "",
  "High precision with low accuracy means the measurements cluster tightly but around a value that is offset from the true value, often due to systematic error.": "",
  "Random errors primarily affect:": "",
  "Only the first measurement taken": "",
  "Neither accuracy nor precision": "",
  "Accuracy only": "",
  "Precision": "",
  "Random errors cause unpredictable variations that scatter measurements in both directions, reducing precision. They tend to average out over many trials.": "",
  "Systematic errors primarily affect:": "",
  "Only the last measurement taken": "",
  "Accuracy": "",
  "Precision only": "",
  "Systematic errors push all measurements consistently in one direction (e.g., a miscalibrated balance always reading 0.5 g too high), reducing accuracy but not necessarily precision.": "",
  "A student measures the boiling point of water three times and gets 99.8°C, 99.9°C, and 99.7°C. The accepted value is 100.0°C. These measurements are:": "",
  "Accurate but not precise": "",
  "Neither accurate nor precise": "",
  "Precise but very inaccurate": "",
  "Precise and fairly accurate": "",
  "The values are close together (precise) and very near the accepted 100.0°C (accurate). A small systematic offset of ~0.2°C still counts as fairly accurate.": "",
  "What is the percent error if a student measures the density of aluminum as 2.85 g/cm³ when the accepted value is 2.70 g/cm³?": "",
  "5.26%": "",
  "0.15%": "",
  "5.56%": "",
  "15%": "",
  "|2.85 − 2.70| / 2.70 × 100% = 0.15 / 2.70 × 100% ≈ 5.56%. The percent error quantifies how far the experimental value is from the accepted value.": "",
  "Which of the following would best improve the accuracy of a measurement?": "",
  "Using a larger sample size": "",
  "Taking more measurements with the same instrument": "",
  "Averaging all readings": "",
  "Calibrating the instrument properly": "",
  "Systematic errors (which hurt accuracy) are corrected by calibrating instruments. Taking more readings improves precision but won't fix a consistently biased instrument.": "",
  "Averaging multiple trials is most effective at reducing:": "",
  "Systematic error": "",
  "Human error only": "",
  "Random error": "",
  "Both random and systematic error equally": "",
  "Random errors scatter in both directions and tend to cancel when averaged over many trials. Systematic errors are consistent and do not cancel with averaging.": "",
  "What does the term 'accuracy' mean in science?": "",
  "How close a measured value is to the true or accepted value": "",
  "How reproducible measurements are": "",
  "How many significant figures a measurement has": "",
  "The number of decimal places in a measurement": "",
  "Accuracy is defined as the closeness of a measurement to the actual or accepted value. It is distinct from precision, which relates to reproducibility.": "",
  "What does the term 'precision' mean in science?": "",
  "How close repeated measurements are to each other (reproducibility)": "",
  "The number of significant figures used": "",
  "How close a value is to the accepted value": "",
  "The resolution of a measuring instrument": "",
  "Precision is the degree of agreement among repeated measurements. High precision means the values cluster tightly, even if they are off from the true value.": "",
  "What is 'percent error'?": "",
  "A measure of how many trials were performed": "",
  "A quantitative measure of the accuracy of a measurement": "",
  "The percentage of trials that failed": "",
  "A way to express precision numerically": "",
  "Percent error calculates how far an experimental result deviates from the accepted value as a percentage. A smaller percent error means better accuracy.": "",
  "What is a 'systematic error'?": "",
  "An error that only happens once": "",
  "A consistent, repeatable error always in the same direction": "",
  "An error caused by incorrect calculations": "",
  "An error that occurs randomly in different directions": "",
  "Systematic errors are predictable and consistent — for example, a scale that always reads 2 g too heavy. They shift all measurements in one direction, reducing accuracy.": "",
  "What is a 'random error'?": "",
  "An error caused by faulty equipment design": "",
  "An unpredictable variation that scatters measurements in both directions": "",
  "An error that always pushes values too high": "",
  "A mistake in recording data": "",
  "Random errors are irregular fluctuations that cause readings to scatter above and below the true value. They reduce precision but can be minimized by averaging multiple trials.": "",
  "What does 'high accuracy, high precision' mean?": "",
  "Measurements are spread out but centered on the true value": "",
  "Only one measurement was needed": "",
  "Measurements are close to each other but far from the true value": "",
  "Measurements are close to the true value AND close to each other": "",
  "The ideal experimental result is both accurate (near the true value) and precise (tightly clustered). This indicates minimal systematic and random error.": "",
  "What does 'high precision, low accuracy' indicate about the measurements?": "",
  "They cluster tightly but are offset from the true value due to systematic error": "",
  "They have large random errors": "",
  "Only one trial was performed": "",
  "They are scattered and far from the true value": "",
  "When measurements are precise but inaccurate, they reproduce well but consistently miss the true value. This pattern strongly suggests a systematic error, such as a miscalibrated instrument.": "",
  "In the percent error formula, why is the absolute value used?": "",
  "To convert the units to percent": "",
  "Because negative errors are not possible": "",
  "To make the answer larger": "",
  "So the error is always expressed as a positive percentage": "",
  "The absolute value ensures that percent error is always positive, since we care about the magnitude of the deviation regardless of direction.": "",
  "What is an example of a systematic error?": "",
  "Slight variations in reading a meniscus": "",
  "A miscalibrated balance that always reads 0.5 g too high": "",
  "Temperature fluctuations in the room": "",
  "Estimating between graduation marks": "",
  "A miscalibrated balance always shifts readings by the same amount in the same direction — the hallmark of systematic error. The other options describe random variations.": "",
  "How can you tell the difference between a random error and a systematic error from data?": "",
  "They cannot be distinguished from data": "",
  "Systematic errors scatter data while random errors are consistent": "",
  "Random errors cause scatter in both directions; systematic errors shift all values in one direction": "",
  "Random errors are always larger than systematic errors": "",
  "Random errors produce spread/scatter (affecting precision), while systematic errors consistently bias results in one direction (affecting accuracy). Recognizing the pattern helps identify the error type.": "",
  "A student measures the melting point of ice five times: 0.5°C, 0.6°C, 0.4°C, 0.5°C, 0.5°C. The accepted value is 0.0°C. These results are:": "",
  "Both accurate and precise": "",
  "Precise but not accurate — a systematic error is present": "",
  "The measurements cluster tightly around 0.5°C (precise) but are consistently above the accepted 0.0°C (not accurate), indicating a systematic error like a poorly calibrated thermometer.": "",
  "A lab group measures the density of copper: 8.96, 8.89, 8.93, 8.95 g/cm³. The accepted value is 8.96 g/cm³. The percent error of their mean (8.93) is approximately:": "",
  "0.03%": "",
  "33%": "",
  "3.3%": "",
  "0.33%": "",
  "|8.93 − 8.96| / 8.96 × 100% = 0.03 / 8.96 × 100% ≈ 0.33%. This very low percent error indicates excellent accuracy.": "",
  "A thermometer consistently reads 2°C higher than the actual temperature. A technician can improve accuracy by:": "",
  "Ignoring the first reading": "",
  "Using a larger container of liquid": "",
  "Recalibrating the thermometer or subtracting 2°C from each reading": "",
  "Taking more readings and averaging them": "",
  "Since this is a systematic error (consistent +2°C bias), averaging won't help — every reading is too high by the same amount. Calibration or applying a correction factor fixes it.": "",
  "In a target analogy, four arrows clustered in the upper-left corner (not near the bullseye) represent measurements that are:": "",
  "Precise but not accurate": "",
  "The arrows are close together (precise) but away from the bullseye (not accurate). This classic target analogy illustrates high precision with low accuracy.": "",
  "A student obtains 78.5°C for the boiling point of ethanol. The accepted value is 78.4°C. What is the percent error?": "",
  "1.3%": "",
  "13%": "",
  "0.13%": "",
  "0.1%": "",
  "|78.5 − 78.4| / 78.4 × 100% = 0.1 / 78.4 × 100% ≈ 0.13%. A very small percent error shows high accuracy.": "",
  "Two lab groups measure the speed of sound. Group A gets: 345, 312, 378, 329 m/s. Group B gets: 340, 341, 339, 340 m/s. The accepted value is 343 m/s. Which group has better precision?": "",
  "Neither group is precise": "",
  "Group A, because their average is closer to 343": "",
  "Both have equal precision": "",
  "Group B, because their values are more tightly clustered": "",
  "Precision is about reproducibility. Group B's values (339–341) are tightly clustered with very little spread, while Group A's values (312–378) are widely scattered.": "",
  "A chemistry student uses a graduated cylinder to measure 50.0 mL of water three times: 49.8, 50.1, 49.9 mL. Another student uses a beaker and gets 48, 52, 47 mL. Which has better precision?": "",
  "The second student, because beakers are more common in labs": "",
  "Neither student is precise": "",
  "The first student, because the graduated cylinder gives more reproducible results": "",
  "Both are equally precise": "",
  "The first student's readings vary by only 0.3 mL, while the second's vary by 5 mL. The graduated cylinder produces more precise (reproducible) measurements than the beaker.": "",
  "A researcher notices that all mass readings from a new balance are about 1.2 g lower than values from a certified reference balance. This is most likely a:": "",
  "Sign that the reference balance is wrong": "",
  "Random error that will average out over time": "",
  "Normal variation that requires no action": "",
  "Systematic error that should be corrected by recalibrating the balance": "",
  "A consistent bias of −1.2 g in one direction is the hallmark of systematic error. Recalibrating the balance (or applying a correction factor) will restore accuracy.": "",
  "A forensic chemist measures a drug sample mass as 1.234 g. The certified value is 1.250 g. What is the percent error?": "",
  "1.6%": "",
  "12.8%": "",
  "1.28%": "",
  "0.016%": "",
  "|1.234 − 1.250| / 1.250 × 100% = 0.016 / 1.250 × 100% = 1.28%. This moderate percent error might be acceptable depending on the analytical method used.": "",
  "A weather station reports temperatures that are always exactly right but fluctuate wildly between readings (e.g., 20.0, 20.1, 19.8, 20.2°C when it is truly 20.0°C). These readings are best described as:": "",
  "Accurate with moderate random error affecting precision": "",
  "Exhibiting systematic error": "",
  "The readings center on the true value (accurate) but show some scatter (moderate random error reducing precision slightly). There is no consistent directional bias (no systematic error).": ""
